{"key":"processedPost-8885849","value":{"id":8885849,"first":8885730,"last":8909204,"when":1220714959,"utime":"09/06/08 06:29 PM","cleanedPost":"Adding weak liquid coffee to grains can help speed up colonization.&nbsp; Nobody really knows why this is so.&nbsp; I suspect it has as much to do with the lowered pH as anything, but coffee also has lots of food fungi love.<br />Horse manure and/or coir seems to be the substrate of choice, mostly due to texture.&nbsp; Adding gypsum to substrates gives a definite boost in health and vigor. With some species, commercial growers report up to a 20% increase in harvests from the addition of gypsum alone.<br />Vermiculite will help hold water and also tends to stimulate pinning.&nbsp; Just about any substrate but straw can benefit from adding 10% to 50% vermiculite by volume.&nbsp; Good luck.<br />RR"}}